    "gallery_carousel": {
      "type": "gallery-carousel",
      "blocks": {
        "image-1": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/efemera-keep-generated-v5-symphonia-neck-intimate.jpg",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "14k Yellow Gold",
            "text": "<p>Not 18k, not 24k — 14k is a deliberate choice. At 58.3% pure gold alloyed with copper and silver, it's harder than 18k, which means delicate organic tendrils and botanical textures survive daily wear without blurring. The alloy also flows better when molten — filling the finest crevices of sculptural molds that higher karats can't reach. The result: richer detail, more ambitious forms, and a warm buttery tone that looks like the metal grew rather than was manufactured.</p>"
          }
        },
        "image-2": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/efemera-keep-generated-product-lifestyle-gaia-macro-1.jpg",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "Freshwater Pearls",
            "text": "<p>Unlike saltwater pearls (which are mostly a shell bead coated in nacre), freshwater pearls are solid nacre — all the way through. Thousands of microscopic aragonite layers, each 0.3 microns thick, self-organize over 2–7 years inside a living mussel. The spacing between layers happens to match the wavelength of visible light, creating luster through the same physics that makes the sky blue. No two pearls reflect light identically. This isn't marketing — it's physics. We choose baroque freshwater pearls because their irregular shapes suggest their own settings, their own compositions. They're pearls that look like they belong in nature.</p>"
          }
        },
        "image-3": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify://shop_images/efemera-keep-generated-product-lifestyle-butterfly-macro-3.jpg",
            "focal_point": "image_presentation",
            "title": "Hand-Painted Enamel",
            "text": "<p>Each Draped in Time ring is hand-enameled on sterling silver — the metal with the highest reflectivity of any element, which is why colors appear so vivid against it. Using fine brushes, the jeweler fills each polka dot, each stripe, each marble swirl individually. The viscosity, the air bubbles, the surface tension — all vary with each application. This is why no two rings are twins, only sisters. The enamel is cured, leveled, and polished to a high gloss. What looks like simple color is actually hours of layered handwork on a 3,000-year-old technique.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
