    "collapsible_row_list": {
      "type": "collapsible-row-list",
      "blocks": {
        "item-1": {
          "type": "item",
          "settings": {
            "expand_by_default": false,
            "icon": "leaf",
            "title": "Moonstone",
            "text": "<p>That floating blue glow — adularescence — comes from layers 0.5 microns thick formed when ancient magma cooled millions of years ago. Two intermixed feldspar species separated at the molecular level, creating lamellae that scatter light through Rayleigh scattering. We cut every moonstone as a cabochon — the smooth dome focuses scattered light into a single luminous band. A faceted moonstone would destroy the glow. It's the most organic gemstone behavior available: a stone that shifts and breathes, the antithesis of a diamond's controlled brilliance.</p>"
          }
        },
        "item-2": {
          "type": "item",
          "settings": {
            "expand_by_default": false,
            "icon": "t-shirt",
            "title": "Aquamarine",
            "text": "<p>The name literally means \"water of the sea.\" Iron traces in beryl crystal create the blue-green that Roman fishermen once carried as a talisman for safe voyages. We cut our aquamarine as cabochons — unconventional, but deliberate. Where a faceted aquamarine looks like ice, a cabochon aquamarine looks like the sea: a deep, still pool of color, glowing rather than glinting. The smooth dome integrates seamlessly with flowing gold forms, becoming a luminous presence within the piece rather than fighting against it.</p>"
          }
        },
        "item-3": {
          "type": "item",
          "settings": {
            "expand_by_default": false,
            "icon": "package-open",
            "title": "African Tourmaline",
            "text": "<p>Tourmaline occurs in more colors than any other gemstone — its crystal structure can incorporate nearly every element on the periodic table. Our tourmalines come from African artisanal mines in Mozambique and Tanzania, where miners work family-owned claims with hand tools. Mozambican copper-bearing tourmalines glow with an almost internal neon light. Tanzanian chrome tourmalines produce an electric green colored by the same elements as emerald. We choose African sources for both the extraordinary color saturation and the traceable, transparent supply chain — knowing where the stone came from and who pulled it from the earth.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
